# EnergyQueue — Cursor Rules

## Project
A carbon-aware distributed task queue in Python. Schedules ML training jobs based on real-time electricity grid carbon intensity.

## Stack
- Python 3.11+
- Redis (via redis-py, async)
- AsyncIO for concurrency
- PyTorch + CIFAR-10 for ML jobs
- CodeCarbon for energy measurement
- Electricity Maps API for carbon data
- Streamlit for dashboard
- Docker + Docker Compose
- Pytest for testing

## Code Style Rules
- Always use async/await — never blocking calls
- Type hints on every function (def foo(x: int) -> str:)
- Docstrings on every class and function
- No print() statements — use Python logging module
- Constants in UPPER_CASE at top of file
- Keep functions small — one job per function
- Raise specific exceptions, never bare `except:`

## What NOT to do
- Do not use Celery — we are building our own queue
- Do not use threading — use asyncio only
- Do not hardcode Redis URLs — use environment variables
- Do not generate frontend code unless asked
- Do not install packages not in requirements.txt